<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="578" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="17.[132,775,1842,2028]" box="[132,283,1842,1868]" pageId="17" pageNumber="578">DESCRIPTION</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[132,775,1842,2028]" lastBlockId="17.[813,1457,215,369]" pageId="17" pageNumber="578">
Massive colony, 
<quantity box="[317,452,1873,1900]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.3" metricValueMax="6.4" metricValueMin="6.2" pageId="17" pageNumber="578" unit="mm" value="6.3" valueMax="6.4" valueMin="6.2">6.2-6.4 mm</quantity>
in thickness, with indistinct endozone. Autozooecia growing from epitheca at high angles. Autozooecia in outer exozone often developing from mesozooecia. Autozooecial diaphragms common to rare, planar, curved proximally, irregularly spaced in autozooecia. Mesozooecia common, up to 3 surrounding each autozooecial aperture, bearing abundant straight diaphragms. Autozooecial walls fine fibrous microstructure, 
<quantity box="[815,1011,311,338]" metricMagnitude="-6" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.5" metricValueMax="10.0" metricValueMin="5.0" pageId="17" pageNumber="578" unit="mm" value="0.0075" valueMax="0.01" valueMin="0.005">
<geoCoordinate box="[815,881,311,338]" degrees="0.005" direction="north" orientation="latitude" pageId="17" pageNumber="578" precision="55" value="0.005">0.005</geoCoordinate>
<geoCoordinate box="[881,956,311,338]" degrees="0.010" direction="west" orientation="longitude" pageId="17" pageNumber="578" precision="55" value="-0.01">-0.010</geoCoordinate>
mm
</quantity>
thick in endozone and 
<quantity box="[1290,1457,311,337]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" metricValueMax="3.0" metricValueMin="2.0" pageId="17" pageNumber="578" unit="mm" value="0.025" valueMax="0.03" valueMin="0.02">0.02-0.03 mm</quantity>
thick in exozone.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[811,1456,407,815]" box="[813,961,407,433]" pageId="17" pageNumber="578">COMPARISON</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="578" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="17.[811,1456,407,815]" pageId="17" pageNumber="578">
<taxonomicName box="[813,988,438,465]" class="Stenolaemata" family="Diplotrypidae" genus="Diplotrypa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trepostomatida" pageId="17" pageNumber="578" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="species" species="undefined-A">
<emphasis box="[813,927,438,464]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="578">Diplotrypa</emphasis>
sp. A
</taxonomicName>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Coryell, 1921" authorityName="Coryell" authorityYear="1921" class="Stenolaemata" family="Diplotrypidae" genus="Diplotrypa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trepostomatida" pageId="17" pageNumber="578" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="species" species="catenulata">
<emphasis box="[1129,1359,438,464]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="578">Diplotrypa catenulata</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="CORYELL H. N." pageId="17" pageNumber="578" pagination="261 - 340" refId="ref20007" refString="CORYELL H. N. 1921. - Bryozoan faunas of the Stone River Group of Central Tennessee. Proceedings of Indiana Academy of Sciences 1921: 261 - 340." type="journal article" year="1921">Coryell, 1921</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
from the Sandbian of 
<collectingCountry box="[1096,1239,470,496]" name="United States of America" pageId="17" pageNumber="578">United States</collectingCountry>
. 
<bibRefCitation author="CORYELL H. N." box="[1246,1455,470,497]" pageId="17" pageNumber="578" pagination="261 - 340" refId="ref20007" refString="CORYELL H. N. 1921. - Bryozoan faunas of the Stone River Group of Central Tennessee. Proceedings of Indiana Academy of Sciences 1921: 261 - 340." type="journal article" year="1921">Coryell [1921: 296]</bibRefCitation>
gave only the spacing of 4-4.5 apertures per 
<quantity box="[1286,1350,502,529]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="17" pageNumber="578" unit="mm" value="2.0">2 mm</quantity>
(distance from centre to centre 
<quantity box="[1054,1219,534,561]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.699999999999999" metricValueMax="5.0" metricValueMin="4.4" pageId="17" pageNumber="578" unit="mm" value="0.47" valueMax="0.5" valueMin="0.44">0.44-0.50 mm</quantity>
), which is more than double as large as the aperture spacing of the present material (average distance from centre to centre 
<quantity box="[1288,1394,598,624]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.2" pageId="17" pageNumber="578" unit="mm" value="0.22">0.22 mm</quantity>
). Size of apertures for 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Coryell" authorityYear="1921" box="[994,1227,630,656]" class="Stenolaemata" family="Diplotrypidae" genus="Diplotrypa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trepostomatida" pageId="17" pageNumber="578" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="species" species="catenulata">
<emphasis box="[994,1227,630,656]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="578">Diplotrypa catenulata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
recorded by 
<bibRefCitation author="ASTROVA G. G." pageId="17" pageNumber="578" pagination="1 - 432" refId="ref18571" refString="ASTROVA G. G. 1965. - Morphology, history of development and system of the Ordovician and Silurian Bryozoa. Trudy Paleontologicheskogo Instituta Akademii Nauk SSSR 106: 1 - 432 [in Russian]." type="journal article" year="1965">Astrova (1965: 185-186)</bibRefCitation>
from the Middle Ordovician of Arctic, was given as 
<quantity box="[905,1065,693,720]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.85" metricValueMax="7.5" metricValueMin="4.2" pageId="17" pageNumber="578" unit="mm" value="0.585" valueMax="0.75" valueMin="0.42">0.42-0.75 mm</quantity>
(with macrozooecia of 0.9-1.0 mm width). 
<taxonomicName box="[905,1089,725,752]" class="Stenolaemata" family="Diplotrypidae" genus="Diplotrypa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trepostomatida" pageId="17" pageNumber="578" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="species" species="undefined-A">
<emphasis box="[905,1022,725,751]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="578">Diplotrypa</emphasis>
sp. A
</taxonomicName>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Astrova, 1965" authorityName="Astrova" authorityYear="1965" class="Stenolaemata" family="Diplotrypidae" genus="Diplotrypa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trepostomatida" pageId="17" pageNumber="578" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="species" species="pusilla">
<emphasis box="[1245,1354,725,751]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="578">D. pusilla</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="ASTROVA G. G." pageId="17" pageNumber="578" pagination="1 - 432" refId="ref18571" refString="ASTROVA G. G. 1965. - Morphology, history of development and system of the Ordovician and Silurian Bryozoa. Trudy Paleontologicheskogo Instituta Akademii Nauk SSSR 106: 1 - 432 [in Russian]." type="journal article" year="1965">Astrova, 1965</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
from the Lower Ordovician of the Russian Arctic, but differs from it by less abundant diaphragms in autozooecia.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
</treatment>
